    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - IC BUS SERVICE MANUAL - SEATS - REPLACING SEAT UPHOLSTERY
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="replace" graphiccount="4">
        <title>REPLACING SEAT UPHOLSTERY</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <para>The following procedure should be used to replace seat upholstery. In most cases the seat will not
                have to be removed from the bus. Refer to
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700186">Figure 77</hotlnk>,
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700187">Figure 78</hotlnk>,
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700188">Figure 79</hotlnk>, and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700189">Figure 80</hotlnk>.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700186" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700186.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="514px"
                         resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 76. Enlarged View Of Seat Assembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f4700187" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700187.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="514px"
                         resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 77. Driver's Seat Belt Installation</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f4700188" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700188.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="514px"
                         resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 78. Enlarged View Of Crash Barrier</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. FRAME TUBING</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. BACK PAN</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. FOAM PADDING</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. UPHOLSTERY</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. TACK STRIP</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. RETAINER TRIM</callout1>
                    <callout1>7. SCREW #8 X 1/2 INCH</callout1>
                    <callout1>8. LOCK WASHER 5/16 INCH</callout1>
                    <callout1>9. FLAT LOCK WASHER 5/16 INCH</callout1>
                    <callout1>10. HEX NUT 5/16 INCH - 18</callout1>
                    <callout1>11. CAP SCREW 5/16 INCH - 18</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f4700189" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700189.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="514px"
                         resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 79. Enlarged View Of Crash Barrier And Hand Rail</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. HAND RAIL FOOT ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. RIVET</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. SCREWS</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. FASTENERS</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>SEAT CUSHION</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the mounting attachment hardware of the seat board bottom.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the seat cushion.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the staples in the seat board that hold the upholstery in place with a pair of
                    needle nose pliers or a flat blade screwdriver.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Replace upholstery or foam, staple and re-install cushion on seat frame.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>SEAT BACK UPHOLSTERY AND FOAM REMOVAL</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the seat cushion.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the staples in the tack strip.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the seat back cover.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">To install, reverse the above procedure.</para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>All seat back upholstery foam is not designed the same, nor does it have the same
                        characteristics. International strongly recommends OEM replacement parts that meet FMVSS
                        requirements.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>DRIVER'S SEAT</title>
            <para>The driver's seat mounting hardware should be inspected weekly. The standard seat may be adjusted in
                six directions. The adjustment mechanisms should be lubricated annually with a light lubricant. The
                anchoring hardware should be torqued at 20 to 22 ft-lbs. The attachment hardware for the driver's seat
                can be located underneath the driver's platform.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>SEAT BELTS</title>
            <para>All seat belts should be inspected for smooth operation and secure attachment. The fabric material or
                wire braid should not be modified in any form. Check the belts for torn or unraveled seams. If found,
                replace without delay. The belts should be cleaned with mild soap and water and air dried. Remove any
                knots or other obstructions that will not allow the belts to function properly.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
